# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: branch-prediction-hw
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] In computer architecture, a **branch predictor** is a digital circuit that tries to guess which way a branch (e.g., an if–then–else structure) will go before this is known definitively.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The purpose of the branch predictor is to improve the flow in the instruction pipeline.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Branch predictors play a critical role in achieving high performance in many modern pipelined microprocessor architectures.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Two-way branching is usually implemented with a conditional jump instruction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A conditional jump can either be "taken" and jump to a different place in program memory, or it can be "not taken" and continue execution immediately after the conditional jump.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] It is not known for certain whether a conditional jump will be taken or not taken until the condition has been calculated and the conditional jump has passed the execution stage in the instruction pipeline (see fig.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Without branch prediction, the processor would have to wait until the conditional jump instruction has passed the execute stage before the next instruction can enter the fetch stage in the pipeline.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The branch predictor attempts to avoid this waste of time by trying to guess whether the conditional jump is most likely to be taken or not taken.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The branch that is guessed to be the most likely is then fetched and speculatively executed.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] If it is later detected that the guess was wrong, then the speculatively executed or partially executed instructions are discarded and the pipeline starts over with the correct branch, incurring a delay.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The time that is wasted in case of a **branch misprediction** is equal to the number of stages in the pipeline from the fetch stage to the execute stage.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Modern microprocessors tend to have quite long pipelines so that the misprediction delay is between 10 and 20 clock cycles.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] As a result, making a pipeline longer increases the need for a more advanced branch predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The first time a conditional jump instruction is encountered, there is not much information to base a prediction on.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] However, the branch predictor keeps records of whether or not branches are taken, so when it encounters a conditional jump that has been seen several times before, it can base the prediction on the recorded history.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The branch predictor may, for example, recognize that the conditional jump is taken more often than not, or that it is taken every second time.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Branch prediction is not the same as branch target prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Branch prediction attempts to guess whether a conditional jump will be taken or not.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Branch target prediction attempts to guess the target of a taken conditional or unconditional jump before it is computed by decoding and executing the instruction itself.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Branch prediction and branch target prediction are often combined into the same circuitry.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Static prediction is the simplest branch prediction technique because it does not rely on information about the dynamic history of code executing.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Instead, it predicts the outcome of a branch based solely on the branch instruction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Early implementations of SPARC and MIPS (two of the first commercial RISC architectures) used single-direction static branch prediction: they always predict that a conditional jump will not be taken, so they always fetch the next sequential instruction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Only when the branch or jump is evaluated and found to be taken, does the instruction pointer get set to a non-sequential address.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Both CPUs fetch instructions in one cycle and evaluate branches in the decode stage.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] As a result, the branch target recurrence is two cycles long, and the machine always fetches the instruction immediately after any taken branch.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Both architectures define branch delay slots in order to utilize these fetched instructions.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A more-advanced form of static prediction assumes that backward branches will be taken and forward branches will not.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] (A backward branch is one that has a target address that is lower than its own address.) This rule increases prediction accuracy in loops, which can be constructed with a backward branch at the end that is mostly taken, or a forward branch at the beginning that is mostly not taken.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] With processors that use this prediction method, ordering the instructions can maximize branch-prediction accuracy.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The RISC-V ISA recommends that software written for RISC-V harts (hardware threads), or generated to run on RISC-V harts, be optimized with the assumption that backward branches are taken and forward branches are not.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Some processors accept branch-prediction hints that override the static prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The Intel Pentium 4 and Pentium 4E accept branch-prediction hints as prefixes.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] In the presence of dynamic prediction, static prediction offers almost no benefit, and overriding the static prediction helps even less.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Intel's subsequent Pentium M and Core2 processors ignore branch-prediction hint prefixes.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] No x86 manufacturer has re-introduced prediction hints.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Dynamic branch predictors naturally fall back on static branch prediction when they have no cached information (such as the first time a given branch is encountered).
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Both the Motorola MPC7450 (G4e) and the Intel Pentium 4 fall back on static prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] In static prediction, all decisions are made at compile time, before the execution of the program.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Dynamic branch prediction uses information about taken or not-taken branches gathered at run-time to predict the outcome of a branch.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Random branch prediction means taking a random guess at whether a branch will be taken, each time it is executed.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The cost for a pseudorandom number generator is low compared to other techniques.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Random prediction guarantees a 50% correct prediction rate that cannot be increased or reduced by any means.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] (And it makes timing even more nondeterministic or unpredictable than other methods.) Static branch prediction (assuming forward branches are taken and backward branches are not) predicts each branch with an accuracy ranging from 0% to 100%, with the overall success rate somewhere in-between.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Unoptimized code is very likely to run with better than 50% prediction success; even 90% is likely.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] If the compiler does some instruction reordering, it makes the correct branch prediction rate higher than for unoptimized code.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Static branch prediction long ago surpassed random branch prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Dynamic branch prediction has surpassed static branch prediction and is commonplace, despite the added complexity.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Some superscalar processors (MIPS R8000, Alpha 21264, and Alpha 21464 (EV8)) fetch each line of instructions with a pointer to the next line.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] This next-line predictor handles branch target prediction as well as branch direction prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] When a next-line predictor points to aligned groups of 2, 4, or 8 instructions, the branch target will usually not be the first instruction fetched, and so the initial instructions fetched are wasted.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Assuming for simplicity, a uniform distribution of branch targets, 0.5, 1.5, and 3.5 instructions fetched are discarded, respectively.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Since the branch itself will generally not be the last instruction in an aligned group, instructions after the taken branch (or its delay slot) will be discarded.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Once again, assuming a uniform distribution of branch instruction placements, 0.5, 1.5, and 3.5 instructions fetched are discarded.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The discarded instructions at the branch and destination lines add up to nearly a complete fetch cycle, even for a single-cycle next-line predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A 1-bit saturating counter (essentially a flip-flop) records the last outcome of the branch.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] This is the most simple version of dynamic branch predictor possible, although it is not very accurate.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] When a branch is evaluated, the corresponding state machine is updated.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Branches evaluated as not taken change the state toward strongly not taken, and branches evaluated as taken change the state toward strongly taken.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The advantage of the two-bit counter scheme over a one-bit scheme is that a conditional jump has to deviate twice from what it has done most in the past before the prediction changes.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] For example, a loop-closing conditional jump is mispredicted once rather than twice.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The original, non-MMX Intel Pentium processor uses a saturating counter, though with an imperfect implementation.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] On the SPEC'89 benchmarks, very large bimodal predictors saturate at 93.5% correct, once every branch maps to a unique counter.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The predictor table is indexed with the instruction address bits, so that the processor can fetch a prediction for every instruction before the instruction is decoded.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The Two-Level Branch Predictor, also referred to as Correlation-Based Branch Predictor, uses a two-dimensional table of counters, also called "Pattern History Table".
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] If an `if` statement is executed three times, the decision made on the third execution might depend upon whether the previous two were taken or not.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] In such scenarios, a two-level adaptive predictor works more efficiently than a saturation counter.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Conditional jumps that are taken every second time or have some other regularly recurring pattern are not predicted well by the saturating counter.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A two-level adaptive predictor remembers the history of the last n occurrences of the branch and uses one saturating counter for each of the possible 2n history patterns.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] This means that the last two occurrences of the branch are stored in a two-bit shift register.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] This branch history register can have four different binary values, 00, 01, 10, and 11, where zero means "not taken" and one means "taken".
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A pattern history table contains four entries per branch, one for each of the 22 = 4 possible branch histories, and each entry in the table contains a two-bit saturating counter of the same type as in figure 2 for each branch.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The branch history register is used for choosing which of the four saturating counters to use.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] If the history is 00, then the first counter is used; if the history is 11, then the last of the four counters is used.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Assume, for example, that a conditional jump is taken every third time.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] In this case, entry number 00 in the pattern history table will go to state "strongly taken", indicating that after two zeroes comes a one.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Entry number 01 will go to state "strongly not taken", indicating that after 01 comes a zero.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The same is the case with entry number 10, while entry number 11 is never used because there are never two consecutive ones.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The general rule for a two-level adaptive predictor with an n-bit history is that it can predict any repetitive sequence with any period if all n-bit sub-sequences are different.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The advantage of the two-level adaptive predictor is that it can quickly learn to predict an arbitrary repetitive pattern.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Yeh and Yale Patt at the University of Michigan.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Since the initial publication in 1991, this method has become very popular, with it being used for later Pentium processors like the Pentium MMX.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Variants of this prediction method are used in most modern microprocessors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A two-level branch predictor where the second level is replaced with a neural network has been proposed.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A local branch predictor has a separate history buffer for each conditional jump instruction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] It may use a two-level adaptive predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The history buffer is separate for each conditional jump instruction, while the pattern history table may be separate as well or it may be shared between all conditional jumps.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The Intel Pentium MMX, Pentium II, and Pentium III have local branch predictors with a local 4-bit history and a local pattern history table with 16 entries for each conditional jump.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] On the SPEC'89 benchmarks, very large local predictors saturate at 97.1% correct.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A global branch predictor does not keep a separate history record for each conditional jump.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Instead it keeps a shared history of all conditional jumps.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The advantage of a shared history is that any correlation between different conditional jumps is part of making the predictions.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The disadvantage is that the history is diluted by irrelevant information if the different conditional jumps are uncorrelated, and that the history buffer may not include any bits from the same branch if there are many other branches in between.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] This scheme is better than the saturating counter scheme only for large table sizes, and it is rarely as good as local prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The history buffer must be longer in order to make a good prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The size of the pattern history table grows exponentially with the size of the history buffer.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Hence, the big pattern history table must be shared among all conditional jumps.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A two-level adaptive predictor with globally shared history buffer and pattern history table is called a "gshare" predictor if it xors the global history and branch PC, and "gselect" if it concatenates them.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Global branch prediction is used in AMD processors, and in Intel Pentium M, Core, Core 2, and Silvermont-based Atom processors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] An alloyed branch predictor combines the local and global prediction principles by concatenating local and global branch histories, possibly with some bits from the program counter as well.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Tests indicate that the VIA Nano processor may be using this technique.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] An agree predictor is a two-level adaptive predictor with globally shared history buffer and pattern history table, and an additional local saturating counter.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The outputs of the local and the global predictors are XORed with each other to give the final prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The purpose is to reduce contentions in the pattern history table where two branches with opposite prediction happen to share the same entry in the pattern history table.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A hybrid predictor, also called combined predictor, implements more than one prediction mechanism.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The final prediction is based either on a meta-predictor that remembers which of the predictors has made the best predictions in the past, or a majority vote function based on an odd number of different predictors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Scott McFarling proposed combined branch prediction in his 1993 paper.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] On the SPEC'89 benchmarks, such a predictor is about as good as the local predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Predictors like gshare use multiple table entries to track the behavior of any particular branch.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] This multiplication of entries makes it much more likely that two branches will map to the same table entry (a situation called aliasing), which in turn makes it much more likely that prediction accuracy will suffer for those branches.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Once you have multiple predictors, it is beneficial to arrange that each predictor will have different aliasing patterns, so that it is more likely that at least one predictor will have no aliasing.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Combined predictors with different indexing functions for the different predictors are called *gskew* predictors, and are analogous to skewed associative caches used for data and instruction caching.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A conditional jump that controls a loop is best predicted with a special loop predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A conditional jump in the bottom of a loop that repeats N times will be taken N-1 times and then not taken once.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] If the conditional jump is placed at the top of the loop, it will be not taken N-1 times and then taken once.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A conditional jump that goes many times one way and then the other way once is detected as having loop behavior.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Such a conditional jump can be predicted easily with a simple counter.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A loop predictor is part of a hybrid predictor where a meta-predictor detects whether the conditional jump has loop behavior.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] An indirect jump instruction can choose among more than two branches.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Some processors have specialized indirect branch predictors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Newer processors from Intel and AMD can predict indirect branches by using a two-level adaptive predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] This kind of instruction contributes more than one bit to the history buffer.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The zEC12 and later z/Architecture processors from IBM support a BRANCH PREDICTION PRELOAD instruction that can preload the branch predictor entry for a given instruction with a branch target address constructed by adding the contents of a general-purpose register to an immediate displacement value.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Processors without this mechanism will simply predict an indirect jump to go to the same target as it did last time.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] A function will normally return to where it is called from.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The return instruction is an indirect jump that reads its target address from the call stack.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Many microprocessors have a separate prediction mechanism for return instructions.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] This mechanism is based on a so-called *return stack buffer*, which is a local mirror of the call stack.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The size of the return stack buffer is typically 4–16 entries.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The trade-off between fast branch prediction and good branch prediction is sometimes dealt with by having two branch predictors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The first branch predictor is fast and simple.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The second branch predictor, which is slower, more complex, and with bigger tables, will override a possibly wrong prediction made by the first predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The Alpha 21264 and Alpha EV8 microprocessors used a fast single-cycle next-line predictor to handle the branch target recurrence and provide a simple and fast branch prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Because the next-line predictor is so inaccurate, and the branch resolution recurrence takes so long, both cores have two-cycle secondary branch predictors that can override the prediction of the next-line predictor at the cost of a single lost fetch cycle.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The Intel Core i7 has two branch target buffers and possibly two or more branch predictors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Machine learning for branch prediction using LVQ and multilayer perceptrons, called "neural branch prediction", was proposed by Lucian Vintan (Lucian Blaga University of Sibiu).
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] One year later he developed the perceptron branch predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The neural branch predictor research was developed much further by Daniel Jimenez.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] In 2001, the first perceptron predictor was presented that was feasible to implement in hardware.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The first commercial implementation of a perceptron branch predictor was in AMD's Piledriver microarchitecture.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The main advantage of the neural predictor is its ability to exploit long histories while requiring only linear resource growth.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Classical predictors require exponential resource growth.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Jimenez reports a global improvement of 5.7% over a McFarling-style hybrid predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] He also used a gshare/perceptron overriding hybrid predictors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The main disadvantage of the perceptron predictor is its high latency.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Even after taking advantage of high-speed arithmetic tricks, the computation latency is relatively high compared to the clock period of many modern microarchitectures.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] In order to reduce the prediction latency, Jimenez proposed in 2003 the *fast-path neural predictor*, where the perceptron predictor chooses its weights according to the current branch's path, rather than according to the branch's PC.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Many other researchers developed this concept (A.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Most of the state-of-the-art branch predictors are using a perceptron predictor (see Intel's "Championship Branch Prediction Competition").
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Intel already implements this idea in one of the IA-64's simulators (2003).
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The AMD Ryzen multi-core processor's Infinity Fabric and the Samsung Exynos processors include perceptron-based neural branch predictors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The IBM 7030 Stretch, designed in the late 1950s, pre-executes all unconditional branches and any conditional branches that depended on the index registers.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] For other conditional branches, the first two production models implemented predict untaken; subsequent models were changed to implement predictions based on the current values of the indicator bits (corresponding to today's condition codes).
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The Stretch designers had considered static hint bits in the branch instructions early in the project but decided against them.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Misprediction recovery was provided by the lookahead unit on Stretch, and part of Stretch's reputation for less-than-stellar performance was blamed on the time required for misprediction recovery.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Subsequent IBM large computer designs did not use branch prediction with speculative execution until the IBM 3090 in 1985.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Two-bit predictors were introduced by Tom McWilliams and Curt Widdoes in 1977 for the Lawrence Livermore National Lab S-1 supercomputer and independently by Jim Smith in 1979 at CDC.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Microprogrammed processors, popular from the 1960s to the 1980s and beyond, took multiple cycles per instruction, and generally did not require branch prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] However, in addition to the IBM 3090, there are several other examples of microprogrammed designs that incorporated branch prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The Burroughs B4900, a microprogrammed COBOL machine released around 1982, was pipelined and used branch prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The B4900 branch prediction history state is stored back into the in-memory instructions during program execution.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The B4900 implements 4-state branch prediction by using 4 semantically equivalent branch opcodes to represent each branch operator type.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The opcode used indicated the history of that particular branch instruction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] If the hardware determines that the branch prediction state of a particular branch needs to be updated, it rewrites the opcode with the semantically equivalent opcode that hinted the proper history.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] US patent 4,435,756 and others were granted on this scheme.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The DEC VAX 9000, announced in 1989, is both microprogrammed and pipelined, and performs branch prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The first commercial RISC processors, the MIPS R2000 and R3000 and the earlier SPARC processors, do only trivial "not-taken" branch prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Because they use branch delay slots, fetched just one instruction per cycle, and execute in-order, there is no performance loss.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The later R4000 uses the same trivial "not-taken" branch prediction, and loses two cycles to each taken branch because the branch resolution recurrence is four cycles long.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Branch prediction became more important with the introduction of pipelined superscalar processors like the Intel Pentium, DEC Alpha 21064, the MIPS R8000, and the IBM POWER series.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] These processors all rely on one-bit or simple bimodal predictors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The DEC Alpha 21264 (EV6) uses a next-line predictor overridden by a combined local predictor and global predictor, where the combining choice is made by a bimodal predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The AMD K8 has a combined bimodal and global predictor, where the combining choice is another bimodal predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] This processor caches the base and choice bimodal predictor counters in bits of the L2 cache otherwise used for ECC.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] As a result, it has effectively very large base and choice predictor tables, and parity rather than ECC on instructions in the L2 cache.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The parity design is sufficient, since any instruction suffering a parity error can be invalidated and refetched from memory.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The Alpha 21464 (EV8, cancelled late in design) had a minimum branch misprediction penalty of 14 cycles.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] It was to use a complex but fast next-line predictor overridden by a combined bimodal and majority-voting predictor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The majority vote was between the bimodal and two gskew predictors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] In 2018 a catastrophic security vulnerability called Spectre was made public by Google's Project Zero and other researchers.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] Affecting virtually all modern CPUs, the vulnerability involves priming the branch predictors so another process (or the kernel) will mispredict a branch and use secret data as an array index, evicting one of the attacker's cache lines.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-misprediction] The attacker can time access to their own array to find out which one, turning this CPU internal (microarchitectural) state into a value the attacker can save which has information about values they could not read directly.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-target-predictor] Branch target prediction is not the same as branch prediction, which guesses whether a conditional branch will be taken or not-taken in a binary manner.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-target-predictor] In more parallel processor designs, as the instruction cache latency grows longer and the fetch width grows wider, branch target extraction becomes a bottleneck.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-target-predictor] In machines where this recurrence takes two cycles, the machine loses one full cycle of fetch after every predicted taken branch.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-target-predictor] As predicted branches happen every 10 instructions or so, this can force a substantial drop in fetch bandwidth.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-target-predictor] Some machines with longer instruction cache latencies would have an even larger loss.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-target-predictor] To ameliorate the loss, some machines implement branch target prediction: given the address of a branch, they predict the target of that branch.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-target-predictor] A refinement of the idea predicts the start of a sequential run of instructions given the address of the start of the previous sequential run of instructions.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-target-predictor] Branch target histories are either stored in a dedicated branch target buffer (BTB) unit, or share their storage with instruction cache.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-target-predictor] BTB can have widely varying sizes, but are typically 5–10% of the size of the instruction cache, the fetch happens much faster than the instruction cache fetch, and so this recurrence is much faster.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/branch-target-predictor] If it were not fast enough, it could be parallelized, by predicting target addresses of target branches.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] In computer engineering, **instruction pipelining** is a technique for implementing instruction-level parallelism within a single processor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining attempts to keep every part of the processor busy with some instruction by dividing incoming instructions into a series of sequential steps (the eponymous "pipeline") performed by different processor units with different parts of instructions processed in parallel.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] In a pipelined computer, instructions travel through the central processing unit (CPU) in stages.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] For example, it might have one stage for each step of the von Neumann cycle: Fetch the instruction, fetch the operands, do the instruction, write the results.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined computer usually has "pipeline registers" after each stage.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] These store information from the instruction and calculations so that the logic gates of the next stage can do the next step.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] This arrangement lets the CPU complete an instruction on each clock cycle.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] It is common for even-numbered stages to operate on one edge of the square-wave clock, while odd-numbered stages operate on the other edge.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] This allows more CPU throughput than a multicycle computer at a given clock rate, but may increase latency due to the added overhead of the pipelining process itself.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Also, even though the electronic logic has a fixed maximum speed, a pipelined computer can be made faster or slower by varying the number of stages in the pipeline.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] With more stages, each stage does less work, and so the stage has fewer delays from the logic gates and could run at a higher clock rate.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined model of computer is often the most economical, when cost is measured as logic gates per instruction per second.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] At each instant, an instruction is in only one pipeline stage, and on average, a pipeline stage is less costly than a multicycle computer.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Also, when made well, most of the pipelined computer's logic is in use most of the time.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] In contrast, out of order computers usually have large amounts of idle logic at any given instant.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Similar calculations usually show that a pipelined computer uses less energy per instruction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] However, a pipelined computer is usually more complex and more costly than a comparable multicycle computer.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] It typically has more logic gates, registers and a more complex control unit.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] In a like way, it might use more total energy, while using less energy per instruction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Out of order CPUs can usually do more instructions per second because they can do several instructions at once.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] In a pipelined computer, the control unit arranges for the flow to start, continue, and stop as a program commands.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The instruction data is usually passed in pipeline registers from one stage to the next, with a somewhat separated piece of control logic for each stage.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The control unit also assures that the instruction in each stage does not harm the operation of instructions in other stages.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] For example, if two stages must use the same piece of data, the control logic assures that the uses are done in the correct sequence.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] When operating efficiently, a pipelined computer will have an instruction in each stage.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] It is then working on all of those instructions at the same time.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] It can finish about one instruction for each cycle of its clock.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] But when a program switches to a different sequence of instructions, the pipeline sometimes must discard the data in process and restart.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Much of the design of a pipelined computer prevents interference between the stages and reduces stalls.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The number of dependent steps varies with the machine architecture.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] As the pipeline is made "deeper" (with a greater number of dependent steps), a given step can be implemented with simpler circuitry, which may let the processor clock run faster.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] A processor is said to be *fully pipelined* if it can fetch an instruction on every cycle.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Thus, if some instructions or conditions require delays that inhibit fetching new instructions, the processor is not fully pipelined.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Seminal uses of pipelining were in the ILLIAC II project and the IBM Stretch project, though a simple version was used earlier in the Z1 in 1939 and the Z3 in 1941.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining began in earnest in the late 1970s in supercomputers such as vector processors and array processors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] One of the early supercomputers was the Cyber series built by Control Data Corporation.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Its main architect, Seymour Cray, later headed Cray Research.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Cray developed the XMP line of supercomputers, using pipelining for both multiply and add/subtract functions.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Later, Star Technologies added parallelism (several pipelined functions working in parallel), developed by Roger Chen.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] In 1984, Star Technologies added the pipelined divide circuit developed by James Bradley.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining was not limited to supercomputers.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] In 1976, the Amdahl Corporation's 470 series general purpose mainframe had a 7-step pipeline, and a patented branch prediction circuit.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] A central element in RISC design philosophy, by the mid-1980s, pipelining was also being introduced into traditional CISC architectures by their developers.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The model of sequential execution assumes that each instruction completes before the next one begins; this assumption is not true on a pipelined processor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] A situation where the expected result is problematic is known as a hazard.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] If the processor has the 5 steps listed in the initial illustration (the 'Basic five-stage pipeline' at the start of the article), instruction 1 would be fetched at time *t*1 and its execution would be complete at *t5*.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Instruction 2 would be fetched at *t2* and would be complete at *t6*.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The first instruction might deposit the incremented number into R5 as its fifth step (register write back) at *t5*.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] But the second instruction might get the number from R5 (to copy to R6) in its second step (instruction decode and register fetch) at time *t3*.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] It seems that the first instruction would not have incremented the value by then.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Writing computer programs in a compiled language might not raise these concerns, as the compiler could be designed to generate machine code that avoids hazards.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The programmer may have unrelated work that the processor can do in the meantime; or, to ensure correct results, the programmer may insert NOPs into the code, partly negating the advantages of pipelining.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] A branch out of the normal instruction sequence often involves a hazard.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Unless the processor can give effect to the branch in a single time cycle, the pipeline will continue fetching instructions sequentially.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Such instructions cannot be allowed to take effect because the programmer has diverted control to another part of the program.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] A conditional branch is even more problematic.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The processor may or may not branch, depending on a calculation that has not yet occurred.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Various processors may stall, may attempt branch prediction, and may be able to begin to execute two different program sequences (eager execution), each assuming the branch is or is not taken, discarding all work that pertains to the incorrect guess.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] A processor with an implementation of branch prediction that usually makes correct predictions can minimize the performance penalty from branching.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] However, if branches are predicted poorly, it may create more work for the processor, such as flushing from the pipeline the incorrect code path that has begun execution before resuming execution at the correct location.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Programs written for a pipelined processor deliberately avoid branching to minimize possible loss of speed.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] For example, the programmer can handle the usual case with sequential execution and branch only on detecting unusual cases.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Using programs such as gcov to analyze code coverage lets the programmer measure how often particular branches are actually executed and gain insight with which to optimize the code.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] In some cases, a programmer can handle both the usual case and unusual case with branch-free code.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] can be problematic on a pipelined processor.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] In this technique, one of the effects of a program is to modify its own upcoming instructions.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] and the modification will not take effect.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] can configure their on-chip cache memories for data-only fetches, or as part of their ordinary memory address space, and avoid such difficulties with self-modifying instructions.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] between instructions, but a pipelining processor overlaps instructions, so executing an uninterruptible instruction renders portions of ordinary instructions uninterruptible too.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] a single-core system using an infinite loop in which an uninterruptible instruction was always in the pipeline.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining keeps all portions of the processor occupied and increases the amount of useful work the processor can do in a given time.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining typically reduces the processor's cycle time and increases the throughput of instructions.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] that require execution to slow below its ideal rate.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] A non-pipelined processor executes only a single instruction at a time.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The start of the next instruction is delayed not based on hazards but unconditionally.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined processor's need to organize all its work into modular steps may require the duplication of registers, which increases the latency of some instructions.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] By making each dependent step simpler, pipelining can enable complex operations more economically than adding complex circuitry, such as for numerical calculations.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] However, a processor that declines to pursue increased speed with pipelining may be simpler and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Compared to environments where the programmer needs to avoid or work around hazards, use of a non-pipelined processor may make it easier to program and to train programmers.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The non-pipelined processor also makes it easier to predict the exact timing of a given sequence of instructions.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] To the right is a generic pipeline with four stages: fetch, decode, execute and write-back.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The top gray box is the list of instructions waiting to be executed, the bottom gray box is the list of instructions that have had their execution completed, and the middle white box is the pipeline.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined processor may deal with hazards by stalling and creating a bubble in the pipeline, resulting in one or more cycles in which nothing useful happens.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] In the illustration at right, in cycle 3, the processor cannot decode the purple instruction, perhaps because the processor determines that decoding depends on results produced by the execution of the green instruction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The green instruction can proceed to the Execute stage and then to the Write-back stage as scheduled, but the purple instruction is stalled for one cycle at the Fetch stage.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] The blue instruction, which was due to be fetched during cycle 3, is stalled for one cycle, as is the red instruction after it.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Because of the bubble (the blue ovals in the illustration), the processor's Decode circuitry is idle during cycle 3.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] Its Execute circuitry is idle during cycle 4 and its Write-back circuitry is idle during cycle 5.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] When the bubble moves out of the pipeline (at cycle 6), normal execution resumes.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/instruction-pipelining] It will take 8 cycles (cycle 1 through 8) rather than 7 to completely execute the four instructions shown in colors.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] The objective is to provide more concurrency if extra resources are available.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] This approach is employed in a variety of areas, including branch prediction in pipelined processors, value prediction for exploiting value locality, prefetching memory and files, and optimistic concurrency control in database systems.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] Speculative multithreading is a special case of speculative execution.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] Modern pipelined microprocessors use speculative execution to reduce the cost of conditional branch instructions using schemes that predict the execution path of a program based on the history of branch executions.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] In order to improve performance and utilization of computer resources, instructions can be scheduled at a time when it has not yet been determined that the instructions will need to be executed, ahead of a branch.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] Eager execution is a form of speculative execution where both sides of the conditional branch are executed; however, the results are committed only if the predicate is true.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] With unlimited resources, eager execution (also known as *oracle execution*) would in theory provide the same performance as perfect branch prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] With limited resources, eager execution should be employed carefully, since the number of resources needed grows exponentially with each level of branch executed eagerly.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] Predictive execution is a form of speculative execution where some outcome is predicted and execution proceeds along the predicted path until the actual result is known.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] If the prediction is true, the predicted execution is allowed to commit; however, if there is a misprediction, execution has to be unrolled and re-executed.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] Common forms of this include branch predictors and memory dependence prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] A generalized form is sometimes referred to as value prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] In computer science and processor design, runahead is a technique that allows a computer processor to speculatively pre-process instructions during cache miss cycles.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] The pre-processed instructions are used to generate instruction and data stream prefetches by executing instructions leading to cache misses (typically called *long latency loads*) before they would normally occur, effectively hiding memory latency.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] In runahead, the processor uses the idle execution resources to calculate instruction and data stream addresses using the available information that is independent of a cache miss.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] Once the processor has resolved the initial cache miss, all runahead results are discarded, and the processor resumes execution as normal.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] The primary use case of the technique is to mitigate the effects of the memory wall.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] The technique may also be used for other purposes, such as pre-computing branch outcomes to achieve highly accurate branch prediction.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] Lazy execution is the opposite of eager execution, and does not involve speculation.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] The incorporation of speculative execution into implementations of the Haskell programming language, a lazy language, is a current research topic.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] Eager Haskell, a variant of the language, is designed around the idea of speculative execution.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] A 2003 PhD thesis made GHC support a kind of speculative execution with an abortion mechanism to back out in case of a bad choice called *optimistic execution*.
[src:branch-prediction-hw/speculative-execution] Starting in 2017, a series of security vulnerabilities were found in the implementations of speculative execution on common processor architectures which effectively enabled an elevation of privileges.
